r\n',1,'2014-01-18 17:27:41',1,0),(4,3,'Lorem Ipsum 2','<p>Lorem Ipsum is simply dummy text of the printing and typesetting industry. Lorem Ipsum has been the industry&#39;s standard dummy text ever since the 1500s, when an unknown printer took a galley of type and scrambled it to make a type specimen book. It has survived not only five centuries, but also the leap into electronic typesetting, remaining essentially unchanged. It was popularised in the 1960s with the release of Letraset sheets containing Lorem Ipsum passages, and more recently with desktop publishing software like Aldus PageMaker including versions of Lorem Ipsum.</p>\r\n',1,'2014-01-18 17:30:47',1,1),(5,3,'Lorem Ipsum 3','<p>Lorem Ipsum is simply dummy text of the printing and typesetting industry. Lorem Ipsum has been the industry&#39;s standard dummy text ever since the 1500s, when an unknown printer took a galley of type and scrambled it to make a type specimen book. It has survived not only five centuries, but also the leap into electronic typesetting, remaining essentially unchanged. It was popularised in the 1960s with the release of Letraset sheets containing Lorem Ipsum passages, and more recently with desktop publishing software like Aldus PageMaker including versions of Lorem Ipsum.</p>\r\n',1,'2014-01-18 17:31:18',0,0),(7,2,'Customs seizes smuggled firecrackers, used clothes','<p><img alt=\"smuggled_firecrackers\" src=\"http://customs.gov.ph/wp-content/uploads/2014/01/smuggled_firecrackers.jpg\" style=\"float:left; height:auto; margin:5px 15px 5px 0px !important; width:auto\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Customs seizes smuggled firecrackers, used clothes</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Posted 17 January 2014</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bureau of Customs Deputy Commissioner Jessie Dellosa (in light blue barong) inspects shipments of firecrackers and used clothing, shoes and bags seized by operatives of the Intelligence Group over the past month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The shipment of firecrackers arrived from China in six 40-foot container vans but were marked as being made in Angat, Bulacan. The shipment has an estimated value of P24-Million and were seized in a warehouse inside the First Tondo Complex in Manila. The pyrotechnics were smuggled in time for distribution and sale to the retail market for New Year and Chinese New Year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the other hand, a total of 1,000 boxes of used clothes, shoes and bags, with an estimated value of P10-Million, were seized two weeks ago in two separate warehouses in Rosario, Pasig City and at the Olivarez Compound in Para&ntilde;aque. A third batch of shipments were apprehended upon arrival at the Port of Manila.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dellosa declined to identify the consignees or importers involved in the entry of the contraband products pending further investigation and filing of charges to be filed against them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Tariff and Customs Code of the Philippines prohibits the entry of firecrackers and other pyrotechnics without import permits from the Firearms and Explosives Division (FED) of the Philippine National Police, while the manufacture, sale and distribution of firecrackers are regulated under Republic Act 7183. Illegally imported pyrotechnics generally do not conform to safety standards set by the PNP-FED. Meanwhile, Sections 3601 and 3602 of the Tariff and Customs Code of the Philippines and Republic Act 4652 ban the importation of used clothing for health and public safety reasons.</p>\r\n',1,'2014-01-22 23:02:15',1,1),(8,2,'18 customs employees probed for smuggling','<p><a href=\"http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/files/2014/01/customs.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://1-ps.googleusercontent.com/h/newsinfo.inquirer.net/files/2014/01/300x140xcustoms-300x140.jpg.pagespeed.ic.f96QHNeNGd.webp\" style=\"height:140px; margin:0px 0px 5px; width:300px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Bureau of Customs (BOC). FILE PHOTO</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>MANILA, Philippines&mdash;The Bureau of Customs said Tuesday it was investigating 18 of its employees for alleged involvement in rice smuggling.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to customs deputy commissioner for intelligence Jessie Dellosa, the 18 employees, mostly appraisers and examiners assigned to the Port of Manila and Manila International Container Port, were believed to have been involved in the processing of rice shipments without import permit in 2013. They were not identified by name.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;We&rsquo;re still conducting the probe. We still have to find out if they are guilty; they have the right to explain themselves,&rdquo; Dellosa said in an interview on the sidelines of the BOC inspection of P800 million worth of smuggled goods in Para&ntilde;aque on Tuesday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Asked if the investigation of the employees had anything to do with Davidson Bangayan, suspected to be a rice smuggler also identified as David Tan, Dellosa said the probe involved the processing of rice shipments without import permits.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dellosa said the BOC was also looking into rice smuggling in an investigation parallel to what the National Bureau of Investigation was doing and that it included Bangayan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;We are still validating reports especially with regards to personalities involved. We are not focusing on Davidson Bangayan alone. We are also looking into other personalities who may be behind this,&rdquo; Dellosa said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Meanwhile, the BOC seized at least P800 million worth of counterfeit goods in two warehouses allegedly owned by the family of Para&ntilde;aque Mayor Edwin Olivarez.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dellosa said the counterfeit goods were discovered in two warehouses inside the Olivarez Compound in Barangay San Dionisio, Para&ntilde;aque City.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The items include imitation &ldquo;Havianas&rdquo; flip-flops and &ldquo;Converse&rdquo; and &ldquo;Skechers&rdquo; rubber shoes, bags and luggage.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dellosa said the consignees of the fake goods will face charges for violating the Tariff and Customs Code of the Philippines, and Republic Act 8293 or the Intellectual Property Code of the Philippines.</p>\r\n',1,'2014-02-19 04:27:50',1,1),(9,2,'Olivarez warehouses yield fake shoes, bags','<p>Para&ntilde;aque City Mayor Edwin Olivarez was put on the spot on Tuesday after a raid conducted by Bureau of Customs agents on two family-owned warehouses yielded millions of pesos worth of counterfeit goods.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a statement, Olivarez denied knowledge of the contraband valued at around P800 million and said he would not condone or tolerate smuggling.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He explained that the warehouses managed by his sister were leased less than a year ago to a company called ZQL Enterprises owned by Richard Gonzales Chang.</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:100%\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"background-color:transparent; vertical-align:baseline\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>Following the incident, his family has decided to terminate the lease agreement, he added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;We will not tolerate this,&rdquo; Olivarez said. &ldquo;We will cooperate with the proper authorities to get to the bottom of this case and we will let the law take its course.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I have instructed our police chief, Senior Supt. Ariel Andrade, to conduct a separate inquiry to get to the bottom of this incident and to file charges against anyone found violating the law,&rdquo; he added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The BOC said the warehouses located at the Olivarez Compound in Barangay San Dionisio, Para&ntilde;aque City, were raided after a month-long surveillance operation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jessie Dellosa, BOC deputy commissioner for intelligence, said among the items seized from the warehouses were imitation Havaianas flip-flops and Converse and Skechers rubber shoes, bags and luggage, and other apparel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to Dellosa, the consignees of the fake goods would face charges for violating the Tariff and Customs Code of the Philippines and Republic Act 8293 or the Intellectual Property Code of the Philippines.&nbsp;<strong><em>With Tina G. Santos</em></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<br />\r\nRead more:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/579010/olivarez-warehouses-yield-fake-shoes-bags#ixzz2thvd2vcg\">http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/579010/olivarez-warehouses-yield-fake-shoes-bags#ixzz2thvd2vcg</a>&nbsp;<br />\r\nFollow us:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://ec.tynt.com/b/rw?id=bSAw-mF-0r4Q-4acwqm_6r&amp;u=inquirerdotnet\" target=\"_blank\">@inquirerdotnet on Twitter</a>&nbsp;|&nbsp;<a href=\"http://ec.tynt.com/b/rf?id=bSAw-mF-0r4Q-4acwqm_6r&amp;u=inquirerdotnet\" target=\"_blank\">inquirerdotnet on Facebook</a></p>\r\n',1,'2014-02-19 04:28:35',1,1),(10,2,'BOC reforms starting to work-Sevilla','<p>MANILA, Philippines&mdash;Four months after its launch, the reorganized Bureau of Customs (BOC) has yet to meet its collection target but Commissioner John Phillip Sevilla avers reforms are &ldquo;starting to work.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/574718/5-farmers-cooperative-officials-charged-with-rice-smuggling/john-phillip-sevilla\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/files/2014/02/john-phillip-sevilla-300x166.jpg\" style=\"height:166px; margin:0px 0px 5px; width:300px\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Commissioner John Phillip Sevilla. RYAN LEAGOGO/INQUIRER.net</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a statement, the new head of the Department of Finance-attached agency cited what he called &ldquo;encouraging initial results.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Four months after rolling out President Aquino&rsquo;s reform program for the Bureau of Customs, emerging cash collections by the agency for the months of November 2013 to January 2014 registered a 19.26-percent growth rate over the comparable period in 2012 to 2013,&rdquo; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last month, the BOC registered revenues of P29.36 billion. The figure, however, was P1.94 billion short of the bureau&rsquo;s P31.3 billion target for the 21-day trading period.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last year, the bureau failed to meet its P340-billion annual target with revenue collections of a little over P300 billion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nontheless, Sevilla, the former finance undersecretary for privatization, said it was a &ldquo;significant improvement from the prereform period growth of 4.76 percent in January to October 2013.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sevilla said that &ldquo;one of the key performance indicators for the reform program&rsquo;s success is the improvement in cash collections.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;One can draw a line before and after October 2013, when the reform operations and personnel movements stabilized, and observe that the initial major elements of the President&rsquo;s customs reform program have been substantive and generated significant growth in revenue for the government,&rdquo; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;These are encouraging initial results. The numbers tell us the reform program is starting to work,&rdquo; he added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Adverse findings</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sevilla said he was also encouraged by the fact that &ldquo;the BOC&rsquo;s Intelligence Group has issued an unprecedented number of alert orders on shipments that were potentially undervalued or misclassified.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Ninety percent of these shipments had adverse or derogatory findings, leading to higher collections for the government,&rdquo; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to the BOC chief, &ldquo;this tells us two things: First, that importers have been so used to the system of corruption in the bureau and colluding with customs officials that they thought they could get away with the gross undervaluation of their imports. Second, with our 90 percent success rate in finding problems in import entries, the bureau is actually not alerting and examining enough shipments.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He reiterated that &ldquo;the work of customs reforms is to go back to the basics and to fix the fundamentals.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said the bureau was &ldquo;committed to closing all the gaps in the system to make it harder for our people to do the bad thing and easier for them to do the good thing.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Early this month, Malaca&ntilde;ang said it was not enough to revamp the BOC. Instead, &ldquo;we need systemic reforms,&rdquo; Communications Secretary Herminio Coloma told reporters.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This year, the agency&rsquo;s revenue goal is P408.1 billion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From 2009 to 2012, the agency incurred collection deficits of P186.5 billion. The revenue deviations totaled P52.9 billion in 2009, P21.4 billion in 2010, P54.8 billion in 2011 and P57.23 billion in 2012.</p>\r\n',1,'2014-02-19 04:40:48',1,1);

